<subSubSection id="C3446530FFB1EC0403C0F8E0FBBDFEED" lastPageId="7" lastPageNumber="325" pageId="6" pageNumber="324" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph id="8BE136BBFFB1EC0503C0F8E0FE84F87C" blockId="6.[151,1437,1830,2038]" pageId="6" pageNumber="324">
<emphasis id="B92AEAA9FFB1EC0503C0F8E0FE86F8CB" bold="true" box="[199,322,1830,1857]" pageId="6" pageNumber="324">Diagnosis.</emphasis>
The subgenus is monotypic and contains only 
<taxonomicName id="4C5E4D38FFB1EC050064F8EEFC05F8CB" authorityName="Whitehead &amp; Steiner" authorityYear="1993" box="[867,961,1832,1857]" class="Insecta" family="Melittidae" genus="Rediviva" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="6" pageNumber="324" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="gigas">
<emphasis id="B92AEAA9FFB1EC050064F8EEFC05F8CB" box="[867,961,1832,1857]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="324">R. gigas</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
which is the largest species of the genus (
<quantity id="4CA69B5EFFB1EC0503A7F88CFEDBF8EC" box="[160,287,1866,1894]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.65" metricValueMax="1.8" metricValueMin="1.5" pageId="6" pageNumber="324" unit="mm" value="16.5" valueMax="18.0" valueMin="15.0">15–18 mm</quantity>
). Males are characterised by a combination of S7 without lateral lobes (with lateral lobes in all other species except 
<taxonomicName id="4C5E4D38FFB1EC050239F8A9FD88F803" authorityName="Kuhlmann" authorityYear="2012" box="[318,588,1903,1929]" class="Insecta" family="Melittidae" genus="Redivivoides" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="6" pageNumber="324" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="karooensis">
<emphasis id="B92AEAA9FFB1EC050239F8A9FD88F803" box="[318,588,1903,1929]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="324">Redivivoides karooensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName id="4C5E4D38FFB1EC050185F8B6FC84F803" authorityName="Kuhlmann" authorityYear="2012" box="[642,832,1904,1929]" class="Insecta" family="Melittidae" genus="Redivivoides" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="6" pageNumber="324" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="namaquaensis">
<emphasis id="B92AEAA9FFB1EC050185F8B6FC84F803" box="[642,832,1904,1929]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="324">R. namaquaensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
), median lobes basally twice as broad as long (
<bibRefCitation id="EFCF4B4AFFB1EC05064AF8A9FE41F827" author="Whitehead, V. B. &amp; Steiner, K. E." pageId="6" pageNumber="324" pagination="143 - 277" refId="ref6735" refString="Whitehead, V. B. &amp; Steiner, K. E. (2001) Oil-collecting bees of the winter rainfall area of South Africa (Melittidae, Rediviva). Annals of the South African Museum, 108, 143 - 277." type="journal article" year="2001">Whitehead &amp; Steiner 2001</bibRefCitation>
: Figs 5B–C) (as broad as long or longer in other subgenera) and S8 apically broadened with margin deeply cleft (strait, notched, emarginate or semi-circular in other subgenera) (
<bibRefCitation id="EFCF4B4AFFB1EC050765F871FA5CF85B" author="Whitehead, V. B. &amp; Steiner, K. E." box="[1122,1432,1975,2001]" pageId="6" pageNumber="324" pagination="143 - 277" refId="ref6735" refString="Whitehead, V. B. &amp; Steiner, K. E. (2001) Oil-collecting bees of the winter rainfall area of South Africa (Melittidae, Rediviva). Annals of the South African Museum, 108, 143 - 277." type="journal article" year="2001">Whitehead &amp; Steiner 2001</bibRefCitation>
: Figs 5D, 64G).
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8BE136BBFFB0EC0403C0FF5FFBBDFEED" blockId="7.[151,1437,153,503]" pageId="7" pageNumber="325">
Females show a unique combination of a broadened hind tibia and basitarsus with the scopa consisting of densely plumose pubescence for transporting floral oil (
<figureCitation id="13652A3EFFB0EC040023FF7BFCB1FF52" box="[804,885,189,216]" captionStart="FIGURE 3" captionStartId="5.[151,250,1889,1914]" captionTargetBox="[192,1394,182,1863]" captionTargetId="figure@5.[192,1395,181,1864]" captionTargetPageId="5" captionText="FIGURE 3. Rediviva (Albiviva) albifasciata Whitehead &amp; Steiner ♀: a. metasoma with distinct white apical hair bands. R. (s. str.) whiteheadi Kuhlmann ♀: b. metasoma with indistinct yellowish apical hair bands. R. (Redivivoides) capensis (Kuhlmann) ♀: c. hind leg. R. (Deriviva) intermedia Whitehead &amp; Steiner ♀: d. front leg, coxa with apical hairy spine (s). R. (Deriviva) intermixta Cockerell ♀: e. hind basitarsus with shiny scale-like projection; f. hind leg." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3889569" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3889569/files/figure.png" pageId="7" pageNumber="325">Fig. 3f</figureCitation>
) (in 
<taxonomicName id="4C5E4D38FFB0EC0400B5FF7BFB85FF5D" authorityName="Michener" authorityYear="1981" box="[946,1089,189,215]" class="Insecta" family="Melittidae" genus="Redivivoides" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="7" pageNumber="325" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="B92AEAA9FFB0EC0400B5FF7BFB85FF5D" box="[946,1089,189,215]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="325">Redivivoides</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
hind tibia not broadened and without plumose pubescence) and a tridentate mandible (bidentate in other subgenera). The species has an isolated position within the genus and, among others, collects oil on flowers of 
<taxonomicName id="4C5E4D38FFB0EC0400ADFEC0FB6CFE95" box="[938,1192,261,287]" class="Gastropoda" family="Tritoniidae" genus="Tritoniopsis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Nudibranchia" pageId="7" pageNumber="325" phylum="Mollusca" rank="species" species="parviflora">
<emphasis id="B92AEAA9FFB0EC0400ADFEC0FB6CFE95" box="[938,1192,261,287]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="325">Tritoniopsis parviflora</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(
<taxonomicName id="4C5E4D38FFB0EC0407B1FEC3FAE4FEAA" box="[1206,1312,261,288]" class="Liliopsida" family="Iridaceae" kingdom="Plantae" order="Asparagales" pageId="7" pageNumber="325" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="family">Iridaceae</taxonomicName>
) (
<bibRefCitation id="EFCF4B4AFFB0EC040632FEC3FE9BFEC9" author="Manning, J. C. &amp; Goldblatt, P." pageId="7" pageNumber="325" pagination="171 - 176" refId="ref5988" refString="Manning, J. C. &amp; Goldblatt, P. (2002) The pollination of Tritoniopsis parviflora (Iridaceae) by the oil-collecting bee Rediviva gigas (Hymenoptera: Melittidae): the first record of oil-secretion in African Iridaceae. South African Journal of Botany, 68, 171 - 176. https: // doi. org / 10.1016 / S 0254 - 6299 (15) 30416 - 6" type="journal article" year="2002">Manning &amp; Goldblatt 2002</bibRefCitation>
, 
<bibRefCitation id="EFCF4B4AFFB0EC04026DFEEEFE60FEC9" author="Manning, J. C. &amp; Goldblatt, P." box="[362,420,296,323]" pageId="7" pageNumber="325" pagination="459 - 474" refId="ref6062" refString="Manning, J. C. &amp; Goldblatt, P. (2005) Radiation of pollination systems in the Cape genus Tritoniopsis (Iridaceae: Crocoidae) and the development of bimodal pollination strategies. International Journal of Plant Science, 166, 459 - 474. https: // doi. org / 10.1086 / 428703" type="journal article" year="2005">2005</bibRefCitation>
) and 
<taxonomicName id="4C5E4D38FFB0EC0402E6FEEFFD7EFEC9" box="[481,698,297,323]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Stilbaceae" genus="Ixianthes" kingdom="Plantae" order="Lamiales" pageId="7" pageNumber="325" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="retzioides">
<emphasis id="B92AEAA9FFB0EC0402E6FEEFFD7EFEC9" box="[481,698,297,323]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="325">Ixianthes retzioides</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(
<taxonomicName id="4C5E4D38FFB0EC0401CFFEEFFC49FECE" authorityName="de Jussieu" authorityYear="1789" box="[712,909,297,324]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Scrophulariaceae" kingdom="Plantae" order="Lamiales" pageId="7" pageNumber="325" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="family">Scrophulariaceae</taxonomicName>
) (
<bibRefCitation id="EFCF4B4AFFB0EC0400A5FEEFFB16FEC9" author="Whitehead, V. B. &amp; Steiner, K. E." box="[930,1234,297,323]" pageId="7" pageNumber="325" pagination="159 - 166" refId="ref6693" refString="Whitehead, V. B. &amp; Steiner, K. E. (1993) A new Rediviva bee (Hymenoptera: Apoidea: Melittidae) that collects oil from orchids. African Entomology, 1, 159 - 166." type="journal article" year="1993">Whitehead &amp; Steiner 1993</bibRefCitation>
, 
<bibRefCitation id="EFCF4B4AFFB0EC0407DBFEEFFEC8FEE2" author="Steiner, K. E. &amp; Whitehead, V. B." pageId="7" pageNumber="325" pagination="131 - 138" refId="ref6513" refString="Steiner, K. E. &amp; Whitehead, V. B. (1996) The consequences of specialization for pollination in a rare South African shrub, Ixianthes retzioides (Scrophulariaceae). Plant Systematics and Evolution, 201, 131 - 138. https: // doi. org / 10.1007 / BF 00989056" type="journal article" year="1996">Steiner &amp; Whitehead 1996</bibRefCitation>
) that are not used by any other 
<taxonomicName id="4C5E4D38FFB0EC040169FE8BFD14FEED" authorityName="Friese" authorityYear="1911" box="[622,720,333,359]" class="Insecta" family="Melittidae" genus="Rediviva" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="7" pageNumber="325" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="B92AEAA9FFB0EC040169FE8BFD14FEED" box="[622,720,333,359]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="325">Rediviva</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
species (
<bibRefCitation id="EFCF4B4AFFB0EC040031FE8BFBA9FEED" author="Kuhlmann, M. &amp; Hollens, H." box="[822,1133,332,359]" pageId="7" pageNumber="325" pagination="561 - 573" refId="ref5935" refString="Kuhlmann, M. &amp; Hollens, H. (2015) Morphology of oil-collecting pilosity of female Rediviva bees (Hymenoptera: Apoidea: Melittidae) reflects host plant use. Journal of Natural History, 49, 561 - 573. https: // doi. org / 10.1080 / 00222933.2014.939732" type="journal article" year="2015">Kuhlmann &amp; Hollens 2015</bibRefCitation>
).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="C3446530FFB0EC0403C0FEB7FB0BFE25" pageId="7" pageNumber="325" type="etymology">
<paragraph id="8BE136BBFFB0EC0403C0FEB7FB0BFE25" blockId="7.[151,1437,153,503]" pageId="7" pageNumber="325">
<emphasis id="B92AEAA9FFB0EC0403C0FEB7FE8AFE01" bold="true" box="[199,334,369,395]" pageId="7" pageNumber="325">Etymology.</emphasis>
The new subgeneric name is a combination of the first part of the specific epithet of the 
<typeStatus id="54E58819FFB0EC040631FEB7FAA2FE01" box="[1334,1382,369,395]" pageId="7" pageNumber="325">type</typeStatus>
species 
<taxonomicName id="4C5E4D38FFB0EC0403CDFE50FEE2FE25" authorityName="Whitehead &amp; Steiner" authorityYear="1993" box="[202,294,406,431]" class="Insecta" family="Melittidae" genus="Rediviva" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="7" pageNumber="325" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="gigas">
<emphasis id="B92AEAA9FFB0EC0403CDFE50FEE2FE25" box="[202,294,406,431]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="325">R. gigas</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and the last part of the generic name 
<taxonomicName id="4C5E4D38FFB0EC0401CDFE53FCE8FE25" authorityName="Friese" authorityYear="1911" box="[714,812,405,431]" class="Insecta" family="Melittidae" genus="Rediviva" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="7" pageNumber="325" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="B92AEAA9FFB0EC0401CDFE53FCE8FE25" box="[714,812,405,431]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="325">Rediviva</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. The gender of the name is feminine.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="C3446530FFB0EC0403C0FE7EFE97FE7D" pageId="7" pageNumber="325" type="distribution">
<paragraph id="8BE136BBFFB0EC0403C0FE7EFE97FE7D" blockId="7.[151,1437,153,503]" pageId="7" pageNumber="325">
<emphasis id="B92AEAA9FFB0EC0403C0FE7EFEA5FE59" bold="true" box="[199,353,440,467]" pageId="7" pageNumber="325">Distribution.</emphasis>
The species is only known from the southwestern part of the winter rainfall region (
<bibRefCitation id="EFCF4B4AFFB0EC040626FE7FFE82FE7D" author="Whitehead, V. B. &amp; Steiner, K. E." pageId="7" pageNumber="325" pagination="143 - 277" refId="ref6735" refString="Whitehead, V. B. &amp; Steiner, K. E. (2001) Oil-collecting bees of the winter rainfall area of South Africa (Melittidae, Rediviva). Annals of the South African Museum, 108, 143 - 277." type="journal article" year="2001">Whitehead &amp; Steiner 2001</bibRefCitation>
).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
